# AutoPkg rules

## Sources of truth

- **Repository**: https://github.com/autopkg/autopkg
- **Wiki**: https://github.com/autopkg/autopkg/wiki

There is no canonical "all-recipes" index. Recipes are scattered across many GitHub repos under the `autopkg/` org and various community orgs. Discovery happens via:

- `autopkg search <query>` (CLI)
- GitHub code search across `autopkg/*` and known community repos
- Community knowledge / MacAdmins Slack

## Actively maintained recipe repos (subset)

The most reliable repos for common Mac app coverage:

- `autopkg/recipes` — seed repo curated by AutoPkg maintainers
- `autopkg/keeleysam-recipes`
- `autopkg/homebysix-recipes` (Elliot Jordan)
- `autopkg/grahampugh-recipes`
- `autopkg/dataJAR-recipes`
- `autopkg/scriptingosx-recipes`
- `autopkg/jss-recipes` — Jamf-targeted (largely deprecated in favor of Jamf App Installers, but still in use)

## Recipe file format

Recipe files use `.recipe` (XML plist) or `.recipe.yaml` extensions. Type is encoded in the filename suffix:

| Suffix | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `.download.recipe` | Fetches an installer from the vendor |
| `.pkg.recipe` | Wraps `.download`; produces a `.pkg` |
| `.install.recipe` | Installs locally (rare in production) |
| `.munki.recipe` | Munki-compatible payload |
| `.jss.recipe` | JSSImporter for Jamf Pro (deprecated path) |
| `.intune.recipe` | Microsoft Intune |
| `.filewave.recipe` | FileWave |

Each recipe has a parent (`ParentRecipe` key) — recipes chain. `.pkg` parents `.download`; `.munki` parents `.pkg`; etc.

## Trust info

AutoPkg recipes can invoke processors fetched from third-party repos at run time. Trust enforcement:

- `autopkg trust-info <recipe>` — show recorded SHA256 of parent recipes + processor source
- `autopkg update-trust-info <recipe>` — re-record trust after intentional changes
- A recipe refuses to run when trust info is missing or mismatched — this is a real attack-surface concern, not a nuisance

When integrating AutoPkg metadata into the Patcher API DB, **recipe identity must include the repo + recipe filename**, not just the recipe name — multiple repos can have a `GoogleChrome.download.recipe` with subtly different behavior.

## CLI cheat sheet

```bash
autopkg search <query>          # find recipes
autopkg info <recipe>           # recipe details
autopkg run <recipe>            # execute
autopkg trust-info <recipe>     # show trust
autopkg update-trust-info <r>   # re-record trust
autopkg list-recipes            # local recipes
autopkg repo-add <github-path>  # add a recipe repo locally
```

## Identity / matching for the canonical apps DB

AutoPkg has no canonical app ID. Recipes are named ad hoc (`GoogleChrome`, `Google Chrome`, `GoogleChromePro`, etc.) and the same app may appear in multiple repos with different recipes. When mapping a canonical app to AutoPkg recipes:

1. Try direct name match (normalized: lowercase, strip spaces and punctuation) against recipe filename stems.
2. Check `Input.NAME` in the recipe plist for the human-readable name.
3. Cross-reference with the recipe's `Identifier` (reverse-DNS style: `com.github.<author>.download.GoogleChrome`).
4. **Manually curate when ambiguous** — there's no high-confidence automated mapping. The match-confidence field in the join table is where you record your level of certainty.

## What NOT to do

- Don't assume a single recipe per app. Multiple variants (download + pkg + munki) are normal and may all be valid.
- Don't scrape the AutoPkg wiki — it's narrative documentation, not data.
- Don't depend on `autopkg run` succeeding at DB-population time — recipes can fail for reasons unrelated to the recipe itself (vendor URL drift, certificate expiry, etc.). Store metadata (recipe name, repo, identifier, last-verified date) and let consumers verify at use-time.
